## Loops

Loops run as long as the condition is met. Make sure that the condition is met at some point, otherwise you have an endless loop which will cause your browser to crash.

### Different Kinds of Loops

JavaScript supports different kinds of loops:

- for - loops through a block of code a number of times

- for/in - loops through the properties of an object

- while - loops through a block of code while a specified condition is true

- do/while - also loops through a block of code while a specified condition is true

Loops are handy, if you want to run the same code over and over again, each time with a different value.

Often this is the case when working with arrays:

Instead of writing:

    text += cars[0] + "<br>";
    text += cars[1] + "<br>";
    text += cars[2] + "<br>";
    text += cars[3] + "<br>";
    text += cars[4] + "<br>";
    text += cars[5] + "<br>";

You can write while loop instead.

### While Loop

    var i = 0;
    while (i < 10) {
        text += cars[i] + "<br>";
        i++;
    }

The flow chart of the while loop is as follow:

![](https://cdn.talentlms.com/xccelerate/1560745297_d02%20while_flow.jpg?Policy=eyJTdGF0ZW1lbnQiOlt7IlJlc291cmNlIjoiaHR0cHM6XC9cL2Nkbi50YWxlbnRsbXMuY29tXC94Y2NlbGVyYXRlXC8xNTYwNzQ1Mjk3X2QwMiUyMHdoaWxlX2Zsb3cuanBnIiwiQ29uZGl0aW9uIjp7IkRhdGVMZXNzVGhhbiI6eyJBV1M6RXBvY2hUaW1lIjoxNTY4NTQwMjUwfX19XX0_&Signature=J7q70GOmIRGCm%2Fu%2Ft4Z7Z3STLAwg5A1nJqF3HJwOPN-k2LIovg2-xGC66rgIdKIKeGXk5RxhxJA237Q94y5mQtC119QlVjzUmNpC6afQQTtG7ignLPDw7UUrV3fzyTE-vlYQzPgWe6FC8oj1dDWSeg2KxHuvQAY6vqC5C5CGq4lck8O0%2F7lpdSaQvNJMftK7uyPS40nv%2FdkTHS2aJywXi%2Fr7M%2FCcClzASO%2FyOIMLy0zahfrkRPRjTxMWqriWOfO32gohbua-oW5mQTYqaBfpj3KNl2-LFsonLqKa2Rz8NeT6t3JXyGGcFVGvXNqY7XEI3od2L404EjhrYzpseZHkKw__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAJDCWVQTW4P3KI3XA)

### Do-While Loop

DO while do exactly the same as while loop except it is run at least once.

    var i = 0;
    do{
        text += cars[i] + "<br>";
        i++;
    }while(i < 10);

The flow chart of the do while loop is as follow:

![](https://cdn.talentlms.com/xccelerate/1560745318_d02%20do_while_flow.jpg?Policy=eyJTdGF0ZW1lbnQiOlt7IlJlc291cmNlIjoiaHR0cHM6XC9cL2Nkbi50YWxlbnRsbXMuY29tXC94Y2NlbGVyYXRlXC8xNTYwNzQ1MzE4X2QwMiUyMGRvX3doaWxlX2Zsb3cuanBnIiwiQ29uZGl0aW9uIjp7IkRhdGVMZXNzVGhhbiI6eyJBV1M6RXBvY2hUaW1lIjoxNTY4NTQwMjUwfX19XX0_&Signature=UpEPlP9TB0D9TadLdpr5jWaAtnApusSry1VrN0sXy4eVWtCVrKrxjQqeOUQQn8N5cM%2FBm4kzbq4JMfnkGgiDs-mYPcX%2Fjs35pvK026ld6GpfC4t08k%2FCRqpyVv92%2Frumk%2FhAuwXqrOgkGaztMrkcmO6SQbPGLGqZNqoH7T6sAniRObvUygq0RQCt57c53Q940A4l9yrTJHnjkQj-PunZLvNx4SzDm1AA5Y40pdyEfmOBVpVyYpu9zvuIRor2Kgf83ce2pFYjKoSFDtTxDivws0cnx0dBjDNYYHwzFZswjBj0LWdqGx3Xorskh2aRMCIDI0W0RzDsrC1PELD6M4V0Aw__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAJDCWVQTW4P3KI3XA)

### For Loop

The for loop is often the tool you will use when you want to create a loop.

The for loop has the following syntax:

    for (var i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        doSomething();
    }

The flow chart of for loop is as follow:

![](https://cdn.talentlms.com/xccelerate/1560745365_d02%20for_flow.jpg?Policy=eyJTdGF0ZW1lbnQiOlt7IlJlc291cmNlIjoiaHR0cHM6XC9cL2Nkbi50YWxlbnRsbXMuY29tXC94Y2NlbGVyYXRlXC8xNTYwNzQ1MzY1X2QwMiUyMGZvcl9mbG93LmpwZyIsIkNvbmRpdGlvbiI6eyJEYXRlTGVzc1RoYW4iOnsiQVdTOkVwb2NoVGltZSI6MTU2ODU0MDI1MH19fV19&Signature=JT1U7BzTA2Q-pQnEVZOGnncR%2FaIwQ4kj0qi2iVuiA01Zfn%2FvJVs799aT0QUqqZcGLtNqTgDVdRP-Tc6G1pWNasb1h0I%2F2BESxtyIKmiStk-KR-dSsbBSJEtrSOaqFSVo0dy3Yv0Y%2FUROHau8Sio64llomK1h1OXSIoY%2FEIAoQQ6btjKDIIsg6K4PccZ4TVeftQkV6ZUFf%2FdNNIQXuvZNn1E0i3V0YWiasxamxoFiwsxZEni01e5ZPD9FIdTPSMgfmf4lejngqpxoE6ZnuSP4oYn37CGvnhpYePdaNdp9sRrfH66pK3pkVy7oYRvx2kiTrjR8eMBvsRx4f57eZjfQwA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAJDCWVQTW4P3KI3XA)

`for ... in` is used to iterate over the properties of an objects

Example:

    var obj = {
        a: 1,
        b: 2,
        c: 3
    };

    for (var p in obj) {
        console.log('The value of obj.' + p + ' is ' + obj[p]);
    }

## Exercise

C

Write a loop that logs every number from 1 to 30.

If the number is divisible through 3 it should log Hong instead.   
If the number is divisible by 5 it should log Kong instead.   
If the number is divisible by 3 and 5 it should log Hong Kong.

So the output should look something like this:

    1
    2
    Hong
    4
    Kong
    Hong
    7
    8
    Hong
    Kong
    11
    Hong
    13
    14
    Hong Kong

D

Write a function that expects a number as a parameter. If the number that is entered is less than 0, equal to 0, or not a number, the function should return the string ‘ERROR’. If the number that is entered is greater than or equal to 1000000 it should simply return the number. Otherwise it should multiply the number by 10 however many times it takes to get a number that is greater than or equal to 1000000 and return that number. Consider which loop you will need to use to do this.  
Use a combination of conditionals and loops to create your answer for this question.

When the function is run with the values below you can expect these outputs:

multiplyNumber('Hello');

// An ERROR will be thrown: ERROR

multiplyNumber(10);

// the value that is returned is: 1000000

multiplyNumber(66);

// the value that is returned is: 6600000

Bonus Exercise

E

Maya writes weekly articles to a well known magazine, but she is missing one word each time she is about to send the article to the editor. The article is not complete without this word. Maya has a friend, Dan, and he is very good with words, but he doesn’t like to just give them away. He texts Maya a number and she needs to find out the hidden word. The words can contain only the letter: “a”, “b”, “d”, “e”, “i”, “l”, “m”, “n”, “o”, and “t”.

Luckily, Maya has the key:

“a” - 6 “b” - 1 “d” - 7 “e” - 4 “i” - 3 “l” - 2 “m” - 9 “n” - 8 “o” - 0 “t” - 5

You can help Maya by writing a function that will take a number between 100 and 999999 and return a string with the word.

The input is always a number, contains only the numbers in the key. The output should be always a string with one word, all lowercase.

Maya won’t forget to thank you at the end of her article :)

Output is similar to this:

maya(1572368);

// The value returned is: Invalid Number!

maya(15728);

// The value returned is: 'btdln'

F

Write a function that takes two inputs: a string and a character. The function will count the number of times that character appears in the string. The count is case insensitive.

For example:

    countChar("fizzbuzz","z") => 4
    countChar("Fancy fifth fly aloof","f") => 5

The character can be any alphanumeric character.
